MEDDESK: I understand you'd like clarity on how your deductible works, and I'm happy to help explain that for you.

Your deductible is the amount you pay out of pocket for covered healthcare services before your insurance plan starts to share the costs. Based on your PPO plan, you have an individual deductible of $1,500 per year, and I can see you've already met $800 of that so far.

This means you have $700 remaining before your deductible is fully met for the year. Until you reach that $1,500 threshold, you'll be responsible for paying the full cost of most covered services. Once your deductible is met, your plan will begin covering a larger portion of your costs. For example, outpatient surgery would then be covered at 80 percent, with you paying the remaining 20 percent.

It's worth noting that some services have flat copays that apply regardless of whether your deductible is met. For instance, primary care visits have a $25 copay, specialist visits are $60, and emergency room visits have a $250 copay.

Your deductible resets every January 1st, so you'll start fresh at the beginning of each calendar year.

